h3. Workaround
None.

Today, when the property "jira.issue.editable = false" is set in the status of an issue, you can not create any sub-tasks under that issue.

It would be great if we could create sub-tasks under those parent issues, as we already have other permissions to specifically block the creation of sub-tasks:
 * {{jira.permission.subtasks.create}}

h3. Scenario
{panel}
Jira allows invalid workflow based permissions to be set in workflow properties, causing further problems when using the workflow or consuming the mypermissions REST endpoint.
{panel}
h3. Steps to reproduce
{panel}
 # In an active workflow, add the following property to a status:
{code:java}
jira.permission.create.clone = denied{code}

 # Publish the workflow and find an issue (JR-123) on that workflow status
 # Access the URL, replacing JR-123 by the said issue:
{code:java}
<jira-base-url>/rest/api/2/mypermissions?issueKey=JR-123{code}
# Observe the call results in HTTP 500 with the following stack trace:
{code}
{
  "message": "Unknown type 'clone' in meta attribute 'jira.permission.create.clone'. Valid permission types are defined in permission-types.xml",
  "status-code": 500,
  "stack-trace": "java.lang.RuntimeException: Unknown type 'clone' in meta attribute 'jira.permission.create.clone'. Valid permission types are defined in permission-types.xml\n\tat com.atlassian.jira.permission.WorkflowPermissionFactory.createWorkflowPermission(WorkflowPermissionFactory.java:86)\n\tat com.atlassian.jira.permission.WorkflowPermissionFactory.getWorkflowPermissions(WorkflowPermissionFactory.java:42)\n\tat
{code}
{panel}

h3.Consequences
{panel}
Such endpoint is used by Marketplace apps and this 500 error may lead to malfunction of key features of such apps.
{panel}

h3.Suggested approach
{panel}
Since "Valid permission types are defined in permission-types.xml", Jira Workflow Editor could check if workflow status properties are valid when publishing the workflow, avoiding future errors upon usage.
{panel}

h3. Issue Summary

When clearing the value of a custom filed via External System Import function.
 The value of a custom field can be removed, but this operation is not shown in change history.
 * It seems a bug since the change history is written when clearing up the value of custom field via UI.
 * Either Csv or Json import do not work

h3. Steps to Reproduce

# A custom filed has value, and be ready to clear
#  Sample Json to clear up the value of a custom field.
{code:java}
{
	"projects": [
		{
			"name": "Scrum Two",
			"key": "ST",
			"description": "This is a sample data",
			"issues": [
				{
					"key" : "ST-7",
					"updated" : "P-1D",
					"summary" : "My test",
					"labels" : [ "ari" ],
		            "customFieldValues": [
		                {
		                    "fieldName": "customfield_10602",
		                    "fieldType": "com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:textfield",
		                    "value": ""
		                }
		            ]
				}
			]
		}
	]
{code}
 

It can be reproduced by CSV as well.
{code:java}
issue-key,summary,test_field
"ST-7","Ny chore3","<<!clear!>>"
{code}

h3. Expected Results

The change history should be written, since it is written when removing the value of custom field from UI.
h3. Actual Results

The change history is not written.
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior.

h3. Issue Summary
{panel}
The CSV import creates new Epic Statues if a column is mapped to it.
{panel}
h3. Steps to Reproduce
{panel}
 # Import a CSV into Jira with a "status column" with values such as "New" and "Cancelled"
 # Map the "status column" on the CSV to "Epic Status" instead of "Status"
 # Conclude the import and the new Epic Statuses will be created{panel}
h3. Expected Results
{panel}
Jira wouldn't allow the creation of new Epic Statuses and interrupt the import.
{panel}
h3. Actual Results
{panel}
Jira processes the import and creates new Epic Statuses, messing up all things Epic related.
{panel}
h3. Workaround
{panel}
Delete the new statuses created:
 # List and bulk edit all Epics from the new statuses to an adequate status
 # Stop Jira
 # Delete the record:
{code:sql}
select id from customfield where cfname = 'Epic Status';
delete from customfieldoption Where customfield = <id from above> and customvalue = 'each new value created';
{code}

 # Start Jira
 # Reindex Jira{panel}

In the last topic of [https://confluence.atlassian.com/enterprise/adding-saml-integration-to-your-existing-user-management-infrastructure-861244976.html#AddingSAMLintegrationtoyourexistingusermanagementinfrastructure-Usingyourapplication'sinternaldirectory] it says that the users have to be already created in Jira:
{quote}
Currently there is no automated way to synchronize users between internal directories and the SAML identity provider
{quote}

With the introduction of JIT (available in Jira 8.6+), we do provide have some automation for the users creation: [https://confluence.atlassian.com/enterprise/jit-user-provisioning-1005342579.html]

Please add a reference to Just-in-time user provisioning to the document, while making it clear that it's not available for Jira 8.5 (maybe it's worth to double-check with the devs and make it clear in the JIT docs too)
